ames ending in Old English <i>cumb</i> ‘valley’ (see   Coombe  ). No such placename as <i>Newcombe</i> is actually on record in Britain.","Americanized form of German <b>Neukamm</b>, possibly arising from a misinterpretation of its etymology as <i>neu</i> ‘new’ + <i>Kamm</i> ‘comb’ (see   Neukam  ).","History: According to family tradition, Capt. Andrew Newcomb was born in England in 1618 and died in Boston, MA, in 1686, leaving family who settled both in MA and in Kittery, ME. Among his descendants was the internationally renowned astronomer Simon Newcomb (1835–1909)."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":84,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":115,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Andrew Newcomben was born in 1175, in Saltfleetby St Peter, Lincolnshire, England, his father, Hugh Newcombe, was 22 and his mother, Isabel de Beauchamp, was 15. He married Alice Adrian Adryan. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1175–":"1175–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1153–Male":"1153–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1175":"1175","1153":"1153","1160":"1160","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","Saltfleet, Lincolnshire, England":"Saltfleet, Lincolnshire, England","Saltfleetby St Peter, Lincolnshire, England":"Saltfleetby St Peter, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1175–":"1175–Kuollut","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1205–Male":"1205–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1153–Male":"1153–Kuollut","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1205":"1205","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1175":"1175","1153":"1153","1160":"1160","1290":"1290","1180":"1180","Saltfleet, Lincolnshire, England":"Saltfleet, Lincolnshire, Eng